Leaving some crumbs for the 4-6 and 10-12 bin just in case a later analysis is revised to reduce a Category 1 hurricane down to a hurricane or a tropical storm to a Category 1 hurricane, given the numerous borderline storms I've seen this season. Probably a post-season analysis will determine this later past the close date, even later than the December 16 criteria (and as late as May or June 2023 based on the publishing patterns of a few seasonal reports I've seen) but it's still not out of the realms of reality that such a revision occurs sooner. Also, we cannot rule out an anomalous hurricane to form past November 30 and before the official resolution last day of December 16 (one full month to go as of today).

Hurricane season ends at the end of November, in 16 days, and there have only been four hurricanes this season according to Kelsey Simpkins, from university of Colorado, Boulder. As stated by Earth Sky there are less hurricanes in November due to cooler ocean temperatures. They also state that there have only been 58 hurricanes in November between 1851-2015. This is less that one hurricane a year on average in a 164-year time span. Lastly a 30-year climate period from 1991-2020 by the National Hurricane Center states that on average there are 7 hurricanes during hurricane season in the United States. In conclusion, I believe that there is an 80% chance that there will be between 4 and 6 hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean during the 2022 hurricane season. This is because this hurricane season has a less than average number of hurricanes in total and ends in a month, November, which has a less than average number of hurricanes. Knowing this it is highly likely that there will not be more than two more hurricanes before the 2022 hurricane season ends.

Based on trends from last year and looking into the predictions for this year, with a 75 % likely hood there will be no more than 10-12 Hurricanes that develop in the 2022 Atlantic season. This is based on the following EvidenceEvidence: NOAA, in an outlook report for the 2022 season, estimated 6-10 hurricanes with 20 named storms (Climate Prediction Center - Atlantic Hurricane Outlook (noaa.gov)). This figure shows that half of the precited number would develop into major storms. With another prediction from NOAA, which offers a 65% chance of the above-typical season, the figure more reasonably fits (NOAA predicts above-normal 2022 Atlantic Hurricane Season | National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration). This number is backed by several climate factors that NOAA lists as contributing to the potential for an abnormal season (predicts above-normal 2022 Atlantic Hurricane Season | National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration). Based on the Evidence provided due to climate factors 10-12 within the season seems plausible.

According to the National Hurricane Center, the average number of hurricane strikes per year is 6.5 (http://www.stormfax.com/huryear.htm). Additionally, Colorado State University has reported that this year will be an "above normal" hurricane season, expecting more hurricanes than usual (https://tropical.colostate.edu/Forecast/2022-04.pdf). Given these two sources, it is best predicted an average of between 10 and 12 hurricanes will occur in the 2022 Hurricane Season, this is also factoring in the reality that this season has already experienced 10 hurricanes (https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/tcr/index.php?season=2022&basin=atl).

AL95 is a new potential cyclone according to the most recent suite of models. I put it at a 50% chance of development, only because the American and European models don't show it becoming a hurricane - at least according to preliminary assumptions I'm making at glancing graphics on windy.com. However, the American and European models aren't particularly good at forecasting hurricane intensities (though they are good with track forecasting). Therefore, I place more weight on the said suite. ~60% with suite alone, -10pp (50%) due to American and European models not showing hurricane development over the next 10 days.

Revising my forecast to account for the passage of time: only in 6% of all years between 1851 and 2021 had we seen 5 hurricanes on October 23 and did the final count arrive at either 7, 8 or 9 (i.e., in bin #3). In all other years (where we had seen 5 hurricanes by October 23) did the final count arrive at either 5 or 6 (i.e., in bin #2)

Following part reasoning of my earlier forecasts but letting go of the correlation with sea surface temperature anomaly as that yielded implausible results. Note that above is what constitutes my prior. I still need to update that based on absence of hurricanes to date - but I don't know how to do that, yet.

So - I have come to the conclusion that my model isn't great. Essentially my model says the number of hurricanes is a function of sea surface temperature anomaly - and I distinguish three categories. The idea is that how lower the SSTA, the higher the number of hurricanes. So far, so good. However, when I compute the distributions based on low, medium and high SSTA and subsequently compute expected number of hurricanes, I get 7.5, 7.6 and 5.7, respectively. Effectively, by my model, it makes no difference whether SSTA is in the (i.e., MY) low or medium bin. I should have checked that prior to posting my first forecast. That gives me two 'challenges' with respect to this forecast question: (i) build a proper model and (ii) figure out how to adjust the model for the fact that we've not seen any hurricanes in the first two months (almost, anyway) of the hurricane season.
